description:
Amid the devastation in Gaza City, young skaters are reclaiming moments of joy among the rubble. Skateboarding has become an escape, helping children channel fear and trauma into movement. 
With parks destroyed and equipment scarce, every board and wheel is treasured, and a surviving courtyard now serves as a training space. 
Coaches work with limited resources to give children a sense of freedom the war has tried to take. Despite injuries and danger, their determination persists. 
Even the youngest skaters continue to practise, finding comfort and resilience on their boards. 
For brief moments, skateboarding restores fragments of the childhood they have lost.

Al Jazeera’s Ibrahim Al-Khalili reports from Gaza City, Palestine.

description:
Norway’s recognition of Palestine as a state was initially celebrated by many Palestinians living in the country. 
However, the decision has brought unexpected challenges for the community, who are no longer considered stateless under Norwegian law. 
Previously, stateless individuals could apply for Norwegian citizenship after three years of residency. Now, many Palestinians fear the process could extend to eight years, prolonging the uncertainty they already face. 
For others, the change could mean returning to live under Israeli occupation to obtain necessary documents, a prospect they had long avoided.
Palestinian Families who arrived in Norway for professional work and those who fled Gaza with their children express concerns over the impact on their lives. 
While Norway’s labour minister clarified that case-by-case decisions would be made for children without Palestinian documents, many Palestinians feel caught in a bureaucratic limbo.

description:
A Palestinian man has shared his account of leaving Gaza through the controversial Al Majd Europe group, revealing details of the process and its coordination with the Israeli army. 
Speaking on condition of anonymity, with his voice disguised and face blurred for protection, he described strict registration protocols that required families to pass security screenings and pay substantial fees, totalling thousands of dollars. 
Despite these procedures, passengers were kept unaware of their final destination.
The man detailed his journey, which included crossing through Rafah and Kerem Shalom under heavy coordination with Israeli forces, boarding buses to Ramon Airport, and flying on a Romanian aircraft to Kenya’s Nairobi Airport. 
He noted secrecy surrounding the destination and the absence of passport recognition, highlighting the lack of acknowledgement of Palestinian statehood.
